# Surface change — holistic follow-through

When you **change behavior, data semantics, or labels** in one place, do not stop at the first file. Treat “fixed” as **verified across the product slice** that shares the same idea.

## Same feature, other surfaces

- **Search the codebase** for the feature name, URL path, `url_for(…)` endpoint, BigQuery model/mart, and any **feature flag** (e.g. `INSIGHTS_ENABLED`). Update every caller: nav, other templates, API routes, tests, and `AGENTS.md` if it documents that flow.
- If the product has **modes or tabs** (e.g. Friday / Monday / mid-week), check **each** mode block in the same template, not only the one you edited.
- If you changed **user-visible definitions** (e.g. “this week”, “open”, “trade”), align **headlines, tooltips, FAQ, and marketing** so wording matches the implementation.

## Data and backend alignment

- If the bug was **data-shaped** (wrong week, snapshot vs history, P&amp;L meaning), check **all** marts, queries, and Python that use the same fields — often the same bug appears in a **list**, a **summary**, and a **pace/hero** block.
- If you add or rely on a **dbt** column, ensure **dbt** ships before or with the app change; call out deploy order in the PR if needed.

## Before you call it done

- [ ] Grep for old strings, route names, or removed UI blocks (no orphan links or dead copy).
- [ ] If templates branch on flags or `mode`, all branches still make sense.
- [ ] No contradicting numbers or labels on the same page (same `week`, same meaning for % and $).
- [ ] Run **tests** or a quick **import/compile** for touched code paths when applicable.

**Anti-pattern:** fixing Pace Check (or one section) while leaving the **same root cause** in “Trades this week”, snapshots, or another tab.
